          <div id="Marketing">
            <div id="myHeader" style="background-color: #fed780;padding: 20px;margin: 10px;">
              <h1 style="color: #3D5161;margin-top: 0px;font-family: Tahoma;">The Pride History</h1>
              <p style="color: #3D5161;font-family: Tahoma;">The significance of celebrating Pride in June can be traced back to a historic event: the Stonewall Uprising, which ignited the Gay Liberation Movement. In the small hours of June 28, 1969, the police raided a popular gay bar, The Stonewall Inn, nestled in the vibrant streets of N.Y.C.'s West Village. These raids were common at the time. But on that fateful evening, the patrons of the bar stood up and fought back, igniting the flame of the Stonewall Riots, which blazed on for days! Fast forward to today, and we're proud to say that The Stonewall Inn has earned its rightful place in history. It was declared a historic landmark by the city of New York in 2015, and even former President Barack Obama designated it as a national monument in 2016.
Fact: Did you know that the iconic rainbow flag, created by the talented artist Gilbert Baker in 1978, holds deeper meanings within its vibrant colors? üè≥Ô∏è‚Äçüåà red is symbolic of life, orange is symbolic of healing, yellow is sunshine, green is nature, blue represents harmony and purple is spirit. In the original eight-color flag, hot pink was included to represent sex and turquoise to represent magic/art, Talk about a colorful journey!</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div id="News">
            <div id="myHeader" style="background-color: #fed780;padding: 20px;margin: 10px;">
              <h1 style="color: #3D5161;margin-top: 0px;font-family: Tahoma;">Mikie OLoughlin</h1>
              <p style="color: #3D5161;font-family: Tahoma;">Who would have thought that after the high of the marriage equality referendum in 2015 that eight years later we would be facing our most tense and most important Pride month in Ireland? It is a very worrying and scary time for gay people in Dublin, and Ireland, at the minute, and in my living memory never have we needed an event to share positivity, colour, and inclusivity more. This colour needs to drown out the shouting from the small minority of blank profiles on social media. If you have a gay person in your life, give them a hug this month, send a text and be there for them. It is just a sexuality, we are all the same and we should all be proud of who we are. </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div id="Commercial">
            <div id="myHeader" style="background-color: #fed780;padding: 20px;margin: 10px;">
              <h1 style="color: #3D5161;margin-top: 0px;font-family: Tahoma;">Aakanksha Surve</h1>
              <p style="color: #3D5161;font-family: Tahoma;">I remember the time I came out to my parents. I was 27 years old and thousands of miles away. I had gotten engaged to my wonderful wife who had just come out as trans and I had to break the news to my parents. Growing up in India, sexuality was a taboo topic and being gay wasn‚Äôt something that was openly discussed. My parents probably never had an inkling I was bisexual. To be honest, neither did I until I hit adulthood and suddenly everything just fell into place. 


<br><br>Anyway, it‚Äôs 2020, the Covid lockdown is in full swing, and I‚Äôm sitting on a really uncomfortable couch in our tiny rented flat in Drumcondra. I tell my parents about my wife and they ask me how I feel about the situation. And despite their mostly supportive reaction, I‚Äôm shaking, I‚Äôm in tears at this point. I say, ‚ÄòGender doesn‚Äôt matter to me. I love the person for who they are and not their gender.‚Äô Now, my parents were no strangers to the coming out talk. Just the year before, my sister came out to them and they were surprisingly accepting. I say surprisingly because my parents grew up in conservative households. Sexuality was never a topic of conversation and I never even got The Talk‚Ñ¢ in my teens.


<br><br>The first time I went to Pride was in 2018 and it was a near-spiritual experience for me. There was a strong sense of community and I felt safe enough that I could be myself. For the first time in my life, I felt like I truly belonged, Sadly, I haven‚Äôt had the chance to go to any other Pride parades in the last few years (both due to Covid and other commitments) but I plan on going this year. I‚Äôm grateful that Ireland has given me a safe space to be myself. I believe the country has come a long way for LGTBQ+ rights thanks to the incredible work of all the grassroots campaigners. That being said, we still have a long way to go. The recent brutal assault of a gay teenage boy in Navan and the growing transphobia in our communities are stark reminders of how we can never get complacent. 


<br><br>We must never forget how Pride Month began 54 years ago after the Stonewall Riots saw a huge number of protests against the horrific violence against LGBTQ+ people in the United States. We must never forget the blood that was spilt to make the world a better place for minorities. As we march down Dublin city centre this Pride, I will be sure to remember our LGBTQ+ forefathers who fought so bravely for us. </p>
            </div>
          </div>

